Part I - Ford GoBike System Data Exploration¶

by Abd Khuffash¶

Introduction¶

The dataset in question pertains to the Ford GoBike System, a bike-sharing program in the San Francisco Bay Area. This dataset provides detailed information about individual bike rides, including attributes such as the duration of the rides, the start and end stations, the locations of these stations, and information about the users.

Calculate the Distance Between Stations¶

In [ ]:
def haversine(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2):
    lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2 = map(np.radians, [lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2])
    dlat = lat2 - lat1
    dlon = lon2 - lon1
    a = np.sin(dlat/2)**2 + np.cos(lat1) * np.cos(lat2) * np.sin(dlon/2)**2
    c = 2 * np.arctan2(np.sqrt(a), np.sqrt(1-a))
    distance = 6371 * c  # Earth radius in kilometers
    return distance

# Apply the Haversine function
data['distance_km'] = haversine(
    data['start_station_latitude'],
    data['start_station_longitude'],
    data['end_station_latitude'],
    data['end_station_longitude']
)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

he dataset contains 183,412 individual bike rides, each described by more than 16 attributes such as ride duration, start and end stations, user type, and trip start and end times. The data is mainly in datetime format (for start and end times), numerical format (for durations), and categorical format (for user type, station names, etc.).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I want to understand how people in the San Francisco Bay Area use bikes, focusing on where and when they ride. I'm particularly interested in how long trips are and whether factors like the day of the week, user type, or age affect duration_sec.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

ride duration (duration_sec) as it gives insights into how long trips are and whether trip duration is affected by other variables, also User type (user_type) Whether the rider is a subscriber or a casual customer Start time (start_time) It can help analyze trends based on time of day or day of the week

Question #3. which hour of the day is the most busy hour for bike riding?¶

visualization:¶

In [ ]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

fordgobike_clean = pd.read_csv('fordgobike_clean.csv')

# Convert 'start_time' column to datetime format
fordgobike_clean['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(fordgobike_clean['start_time'])

# copy the dataset
data = fordgobike_clean.copy()

# extracting the hour from the start_time column
data['start_hour'] = data['start_time'].dt.hour

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.countplot(data=data, x='start_hour', palette='viridis')
plt.title('Distribution of Bike Rides by Hour of the Day', fontsize=15)
plt.xlabel('Hour of Day (24h)', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Number of Rides', fontsize=12)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Observations:¶

The data highlights clear patterns in ride usage throughout the day. There’s a noticeable increase around 8 AM, aligning with the morning commute, and another spike between 5 and 6 PM during evening rush hour. In contrast, late-night and early-morning hours, particularly from 12 AM to 5 AM, see very few rides, indicating limited use during these times.

Observations for User Type During Peak Hours:¶

Customers (Casual Riders): Customers make up a smaller portion of the rides during these peak hours, suggesting that subscribers are more likely to use bikes for commuting purposes. During peak hours, most bike rides are taken by subscribers, who are the frequent users. They make up the majority of trips in the morning and evening. In contrast, customers, who ride casually, represent a smaller share of rides during these busy times. This shows that subscribers are more likely to use bikes for daily commutes, while casual riders use the service less during peak hours.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distribution of bike rides by hour showed clear peaks during commute times, especially at 8 AM and 5-6 PM. These peak hours mean that most folks are using the bike-sharing system to get to work or school. There weren’t any crazy points, but the data showed super low usage late at night (12 AM to 5 AM), which was kinda expected. I had to convert the start_time column to datetime format so I could pull out the hour of the day for my analysis.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The data didn't have any highly unusual distributions, but the bike usage patterns were clearly skewed towards working hours. I performed a conversion of the start_time column to datetime format to extract the hour and day for easier analysis. This step was necessary to investigate the time-related patterns in bike usage.

I observed that trip duration was generally longer for customers than for subscribers. Multivariate Exploration¶

Question 1: How does trip duration vary by user type, and how does this change across the days of the week?¶

visualization:¶

In [ ]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Calculate the 95th percentile to limit the x-axis
percentile_95 = data['duration_min'].quantile(0.95)

# Create the FacetGrid with limited x-axis to remove extreme outliers visually
g = sns.FacetGrid(data, col="user_type", row="day_of_week", height=4, aspect=1.5)
g.map_dataframe(sns.histplot, "duration_min", bins=30, kde=False)
g.set_axis_labels("Trip Duration (Minutes)", "Frequency")
g.set_titles("{row_name} - {col_name}")

# Adjust each axis
for ax in g.axes.flatten():
    ax.set_xlim(0, percentile_95)  # Limit the x-axis to the 95th percentile

g.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Observation:¶

Subscribers have shorter trips across all days of the week, with the most frequent trips being under 30 minutes. Customers tend to have longer trips, especially on weekends, where trips longer than 30 minutes are more common.

Question 2: What is the relationship between trip duration, rider age, and user type?¶

visualization:¶

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.boxplot(data=data, x='day_of_week', y='duration_min', hue='user_type')
plt.title('Distribution of Trip Durations by Day of Week and User Type')
plt.xlabel('Day of Week')
plt.ylabel('Trip Duration (Minutes)')
plt.ylim(0, data['duration_min'].quantile(0.95))  # Limiting to 95th percentile to avoid extreme outliers
plt.legend(title='User Type')
plt.show()

Observation:¶

There is no clear correlation between rider age and trip duration. Both user types seem to have similar trends across all age groups. Customers tend to have slightly longer trips compared to subscribers across most age ranges.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

In this part of the investigation, I observed a strong relationship between user type and trip duration across the days of the week. The box plots showed that customers tend to take longer trips than subscribers, particularly on weekends. This trend aligns with the idea that subscribers are more likely using the service for commuting, while customers are using it for leisurely or recreational purposes. The days of the week also played a role, as customer trips were longer on weekends, reinforcing the leisure-based usage pattern. Subscribers, on the other hand, had shorter trips throughout the week, especially during weekdays.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

One interesting interaction was between user type, trip duration, and day of the week. While it was expected that subscribers would take shorter trips, it was surprising to see how consistent this pattern was throughout the week. Another surprising interaction was how much longer customer trips were on weekends compared to weekdays. This highlights a significant difference in how both user groups use the service depending on the day, with customers favoring weekends for longer, more leisurely rides.

Conclusions¶

Peak Hours: People are hitting the bikes hard around 8 AM and 5-6 PM, just like when folks are commuting to and from work.

Trip Length: Subscribers are in and out faster, taking shorter rides. But customers? Their trips get way longer on weekends—like they're out for a full day of fun.

Usage Patterns: Subscribers are all about those weekday rides, showing they use bikes mainly for getting to work. Customers ride more evenly throughout the week, but they do seem to love the weekends a bit more.

Age vs. Trip Duration: Age ain’t really a game-changer when it comes to how long people ride. Both subscribers and customers have pretty much the same vibes in trip duration across different age groups.
